Wiring Diagram:-

Arduino          L298N Motor Driver
  5   ---------> ENA (Enable A - PWM)
  6   ---------> IN1 (Motor A Direction)
  7   ---------> IN2 (Motor A Direction)
  8   ---------> IN3 (Motor B Direction)
  9   ---------> IN4 (Motor B Direction)
  3   ---------> ENB (Enable B - PWM)

Arduino          HC-SR04 Sensor
  2   ---------> TRIG
  4   ---------> ECHO
 5V   ---------> VCC
 GND  ---------> GND

Arduino          Servo Motor
  11  ---------> Signal (Orange/Yellow)
 5V   ---------> VCC (Red)
 GND  ---------> GND (Brown/Black)

Arduino          Buzzer
  A2  ---------> Positive (+)
 GND  ---------> Negative (-)


Installation:-

- Install the Arduino IDE and add the Servo library from the Library Manager.
- Connect your Arduino Uno to the computer using USB and open the (.ino) file in the Arduino IDE.
- Select the correct board and port, then upload the code to the Arduino.


Troubleshooting:-

1) Robot does not move
Check the connections of the L298N Motor Driver Module and make sure the battery (7–12V) is providing enough power. You can also test the motors directly with the motor driver.

2) Sensor gives wrong readings
Make sure the HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Sensor is fixed properly and the TRIG and ECHO wires are connected tightly. Try testing without metal or sound-absorbing objects nearby.

3) Robot keeps turning again and again
Change the SAFE_DISTANCE and STOP_DISTANCE values in the code and make sure the SG90 Servo Motor is centered at 90°.

4) Servo shakes or jitters
Give separate power to the servo if needed and add a small 100µF capacitor across the servo power wires.
